ment will eventually collapse.<ref>{{cite news|last=Chang|first=Gordon G.|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2011/12/29/the_coming_collapse_of_china_2012_edition|title=The Coming Collapse of China: 2012 Edition|work=Foreign Policy|date=29 December 2011|access-date=9 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=12kSAOWIs5k|title=China's Collapse Is Coming, More So Now Than Ever - Gordon Chang|publisher=Kitco News|date=23 December 2016|via=YouTube|access-date=9 December 2018}}</ref>  Shen Dingli, director of the Center for American Studies at [[Fudan University]], wrote that Chang's predictions \"collapse his own credibility.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Shen|first=Dingli|url=http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/961959.shtml|title=Chang's predictions of China's collapse destroy his own credibility|work=Global Times|date=5 January 2016|access-date=9 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Other activities===\nIn ''Nuclear Showdown: North Korea Takes on the World'' (2006)<!--   ISBN 978-0-09-179970-0 -->, Chang says that [[North Korea]] is most likely to target [[Japan]], not [[South Korea]]. He also says that [[North Korea and weapons of mass destruction|North Korean nuclear ambitions]] could be forestalled if there were concerted multinational diplomacy, with some \"limits to patience\" backed up by threat of an all-out Korean war.\n\nChang is a former contributor at ''[[The Daily Beast]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url =https://www.thedailybeast.com/author/gordon-g-chang | title =Author Page Gordon Chang | website =TheDailyBeast.com | access-date =October 23, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nChang often criticized [[South Korea]]'s President [[Moon Jae-in]]'s term. Chang criticized Moon Jae-in, calling him \"dangerous,\" and said that Moon should be considered \"North Korea's agent.\"<ref name=\"Moon\">{{cite tweet |user=GordonGChang |author=Gordon G. Chang |number=1049364182859014144 |date=8 October 2018 |title=#MoonJaein could be a #NorthKorea agent, yet whether he is or not we should treat him as one. He is subverting freedom, democracy, and #SouthKorea. He is dangerous.|archive-url=https://archive.is/HpTt9|archive-date=28 October 2018 |accessdate=2018-10-29}}</ref> Chang also asserted that Moon Jae-in is \"subverting freedom, democracy, and South Korea.\"<ref name=\"Moon\"/>\n\nDuring the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], Chang praised the US for acting 'very, very quickly' in response to the epidemic.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Creitz |first1=Charles |title=Gordon Chang praises US for acting 'very, very quickly' against coronavirus spread |url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/china-expert-gordon-chang-coronavirus-us-action |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{clear}}\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.gordonchang.com/}}\n* [http://www.dnaindia.com/report.asp?NewsID=1036746 \"Kim Jong-il will create crisis, China will step in and solve it\"], Gordon Chang interview to Venkatesan Vembu, Daily News & Analysis, 20 June 2006\n* {{C-SPAN|gordonchang}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chang, Gordon}}\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:American lawyers]]\n[[Category:American people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American writers of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Cornell Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "31.45.120.65", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eOther activities)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gordon_G._Chang"}
{"title_page": "Haribo", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2010}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Haribo\n| logo             = HARIBO Logo.svg\n| logo_size        = 220px\n| image            = 2013-09-02 Haribo-Zentrale, Hans-Riegel-Stra\u00dfe 1, Bonn-Kessenich IMG 0929.jpg\n| image_caption    = Former Haribo headquarters in [[Bonn]]-[[Kessenich (Bonn)|Kessenich]]\n| type             = [[Kommanditgesellschaft|GmbH & Co. KG]]\n| founder          = [[Hans Riegel Sr.]]\n| key_people       = \n| industry         = [[Confectionery]]\n| products         = Gummy bears, gummy candy\n| revenue          = [[Euro|\u20ac]] 1.7\u20132.0 billion\n| num_employees    = ~7,000 (2018)\n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.haribo.com}}\n| foundation       = {{Start date and age|1920|12|12}}\n| location_city    = [[Grafschaft, Rhineland]]\n| location_country = Germany\n}}\n'''Haribo''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|\u00e6r|\u1d7b|b|o\u028a}} {{respell|HARR|i-boh}}) is a German [[confectionery]] company founded by [[Hans Riegel Sr.]] in 1920. It began in [[Kessenich (Bonn)|Kessenich]], [[Bonn]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]; the name is an [[acronym]] formed from '''Ha'''ns '''Ri'''egel, '''Bo'''nn. The company created the first [[Gummy candy|gummy candy]] in 1922 in the form of little [[Gummy bear|gummy bears]] called ''Gummib\u00e4rchen''. The current headquarters is in [[Grafschaft, Rhineland|Grafschaft]], [[Rhineland-Palatinate]], Germany.\n\nThe [[Museum|Landesmuseum]] [[Koblenz]] created a travelling exhibition about the history of Haribo in 2006.\n\n==History==\n\n\nHaribo has expanded its operations, taking over many local confectionery manufacturers in countries all over the world. It began international expansion in the 1960s and entered American markets in the 1980s. It currently operates 16 factories which produce over 100 million gummy bears per day.<ref name=guardian>{{cite news|last1=Oltermann|first1=Philip|title=Haribo: the confessions of a confectionery addict|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/shortcuts/2013/oct/16/haribo-confectionery-founder-hans-riegel-died-90|accessdate=30 July 2015|work=The Guardian|date=13 October 2013}}</ref>\nI am so dumb\nHaribo was accused of using [[Forced labour in Germany during World War II|Jewish forced labor]] in its factories during [[World War II]], but denies this.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Charles P. |last=Wallace |title=The Final Reckoning |url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2050858,00.html |journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time Europe]] |location=Berlin |volume=156 |issue=5 |date=31 July 2000 |accessdate=12 November 2008}}</ref> In 2014, Haribo's ''Skipper Mix'' was pulled in some markets because some of the candy pieces were shaped like caricatures of Asian, African, and Native American masks that some consumers considered to be racist.<ref>{{cite news|last=Licata|first=Elizabeth|title=Haribo Pulls Skipper Mix After Racism Accusations|url=http://www.thedailymeal.com/Haribo-Pulls-Skipper-Mix-Racism-Accusations/11814|accessdate=25 January 2015|newspaper=The Daily Meal|date=18 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==UK presence==<!--{{Pontefract}} links here-->\n[[File:German sweets and liquorice confectionery.jpg|thumb|A colourful mix of confectionery: Haribo Colour-Rado]]\n[[File:Haribo Sweets Factory - Sessions House Yard - geograph.org.uk - 576986.jpg|thumb|left|Haribo factory in [[Pontefract]].]]\nHaribo's key brands in the UK are Starmix, Tangfastics, Supermix, and Maoam, with Maoam being its own line of chewy sweets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maoam.com/lang/enGB/index.html|title=MAOAM|work=maoam.com|accessdate=27 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150719065925/http://www.maoam.com/lang/enGB/index.html|archivedate=19 July 2015}}</ref> They were once the distributor of [[Pez]] products in the United Kingdom, but this is no longer the case. Haribo makes [[Pontefract Cakes]] at their factory in [[Pontefract]], [[West Yorkshire]], and other locations.\n\n==US presence==\n\n{{Unreferenced section|date=December 2019}}\n\nHaribo had been imported into the [[United States]] for many years{{When|date=May 2017}} by German food importers and sold at German and other gourmet stores at \"gourmet prices\", mostly in bulk. In Germany, Haribo was not an exclusive gourmet product, but a mass market candy. When Haribo of America was incorporated in the 1980s in [[Baltimore, Maryland]], Haribo's gummi candies were introduced to the US mass market through areas such as drugstores, grocery stores, and discount stores. The packaging was translated into English, and package weights were adjusted to match U.S. candy price points and package sizes. A laydown bag was developed for the US supermarket trade, instead of the hanging bag commonly found in German supermarkets, and a boxed product was developed for theaters. \n\nOnce this was done and Haribo products in US-style packaging were introduced at confectionery and fancy food shows, Haribo became a popular item. Sales soared the first year, and gummy bears became so popular in the US, Haribo in Germany could not supply enough products, so the US market was soon flooded with competitors such as German [[Trolli]] and American [[Black Forest Gummy Bears|Black Forest]].\n\nOn 23 March 2017, Haribo announced they will be opening their first United States factory, a 500,000 sq ft (46,500 m\u00b2), 400 employee manufacturing plant in Kenosha County, Wisconsin, scheduled to open in 2020.\nHaribo products made in the US regularly have [[corn syrup]] and artificial flavors and colors. Production with artificial ingredients is cheaper, however, and the U.S. operation is poised to profit from this lower cost.\n\n==International distribution==\n[[File:Haribo Normanton Distribution.jpg|New Haribo factory and distribution centre located in Castleford, West Yorkshire, UK.|thumb]]\nHaribo plans to expand to China and Brazil. In China it has launched test stores in Shanghai and Guangdong. The US headquarters is located in [[Rosemont, IL]]. New production facilities opened in [[Castleford]], West Yorkshire,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-24471417|title=Castleford Haribo plant to create 286 jobs|date=10 October 2013|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> (directly opposite the Normanton M62 Junction (J31)) in 2016 and plans to open in S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Best|first1=Dean|title=Haribo to expand in China, US, UK and Brazil|url=http://www.just-food.com/news/haribo-to-expand-in-china-us-uk-and-brazil_id130630.aspx|website=just-food.com|publisher=just-food.com|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref>[[File:Haribo factories in Europe.png|thumb|Countries with Haribo factories in Europe]]\n\n==Slogans==\nHaribo's [[German language|German]] catchphrase is ''\"Haribo macht Kinder froh \u2013 und Erwachsene ebenso\"'' (\"Haribo makes children happy \u2013 and adults as well\"). The German advertisements were voiced by [[Thomas Gottschalk]] from 1991 until 2015. In English-speaking countries, it uses the slogan \"Kids and grown-ups love it so \u2013 the happy world of Haribo\". In [[Hungary]], it uses the slogan \"''Gyermek, feln\u0151tt kedve j\u00f3 \u2013 \u00e9des \u00e9let, Haribo''\" (\"Child and adult is happy \u2013 sweet life, Haribo\"). \"''Haribo c'est beau la vie, pour les grands et les petits''\" (\"Haribo life is beautiful, for big ones and little ones\") is used in [[France]], while in [[Italy]] the song used during commercials is: \"''Haribo \u00e8 la bont\u00e0, che si gusta ad ogni et\u00e0''\" (\"Haribo is the delicacy that one can taste at any age\"). Similar slogans are used in other languages. The famed Haribo jingle music was created by UK composer Stephen Lee Vickers.\n\n==In popular culture==\n*Haribo is referred to by name in [[Watsky]]'s 2012 song \"Gummy Bear Hundrednaire\" off his [[mix-tape]] ''Nothing Like the First Time''.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bft9zX5VSWw</ref><ref>https://gwatsky.bandcamp.com/album/nothing-like-the-first-time</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Haribo}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.haribo.com}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Candy]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Brand name confectionery]]\n[[Category:German brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Bonn]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Rhineland-Palatinate]]\n[[Category:Ahrweiler (district)]]\n[[Category:German confectionery]]\n[[Category:Gummi candies]]\n[[Category:1920 establishments in Germany]]\n[[category:German snack foods]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2010}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Haribo\n| logo             = HARIBO Logo.svg\n| logo_size        = 220px\n| image            = 2013-09-02 Haribo-Zentrale, Hans-Riegel-Stra\u00dfe 1, Bonn-Kessenich IMG 0929.jpg\n| image_caption    = Former Haribo headquarters in [[Bonn]]-[[Kessenich (Bonn)|Kessenich]]\n| type             = [[Kommanditgesellschaft|GmbH & Co. KG]]\n| founder          = [[Hans Riegel Sr.]]\n| key_people       = \n| industry         = [[Confectionery]]\n| products         = Gummy bears, gummy candy\n| revenue          = [[Euro|\u20ac]] 1.7\u20132.0 billion\n| num_employees    = ~7,000 (2018)\n| homepage         = {{URL|http://www.haribo.com}}\n| foundation       = {{Start date and age|1920|12|12}}\n| location_city    = [[Grafschaft, Rhineland]]\n| location_country = Germany\n}}\n'''Haribo''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|\u00e6r|\u1d7b|b|o\u028a}} {{respell|HARR|i-boh}}) is a German [[confectionery]] company founded by [[Hans Riegel Sr.]] in 1920. It began in [[Kessenich (Bonn)|Kessenich]], [[Bonn]], [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]; the name is an [[acronym]] formed from '''Ha'''ns '''Ri'''egel, '''Bo'''nn. The company created the first [[Gummy candy|gummy candy]] in 1922 in the form of little [[Gummy bear|gummy bears]] called ''Gummib\u00e4rchen''. The current headquarters is in [[Grafschaft, Rhineland|Grafschaft]], [[Rhineland-Palatinate]], Germany.\n\nThe [[Museum|Landesmuseum]] [[Koblenz]] created a travelling exhibition about the history of Haribo in 2006.\n\n==History==\n\n\nHaribo has expanded its operations, taking over many local confectionery manufacturers in countries all over the world. It began international expansion in the 1960s and entered American markets in the 1980s. It currently operates 16 factories which produce over 100 million gummy bears per day.<ref name=guardian>{{cite news|last1=Oltermann|first1=Philip|title=Haribo: the confessions of a confectionery addict|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/shortcuts/2013/oct/16/haribo-confectionery-founder-hans-riegel-died-90|accessdate=30 July 2015|work=The Guardian|date=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nHaribo was accused of using [[Forced labour in Germany during World War II|Jewish forced labor]] in its factories during [[World War II]], but denies this.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Charles P. |last=Wallace |title=The Final Reckoning |url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2050858,00.html |journal=[[Time (magazine)|Time Europe]] |location=Berlin |volume=156 |issue=5 |date=31 July 2000 |accessdate=12 November 2008}}</ref> In 2014, Haribo's ''Skipper Mix'' was pulled in some markets because some of the candy pieces were shaped like caricatures of Asian, African, and Native American masks that some consumers considered to be racist.<ref>{{cite news|last=Licata|first=Elizabeth|title=Haribo Pulls Skipper Mix After Racism Accusations|url=http://www.thedailymeal.com/Haribo-Pulls-Skipper-Mix-Racism-Accusations/11814|accessdate=25 January 2015|newspaper=The Daily Meal|date=18 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n==UK presence==<!--{{Pontefract}} links here-->\n[[File:German sweets and liquorice confectionery.jpg|thumb|A colourful mix of confectionery: Haribo Colour-Rado]]\n[[File:Haribo Sweets Factory - Sessions House Yard - geograph.org.uk - 576986.jpg|thumb|left|Haribo factory in [[Pontefract]].]]\nHaribo's key brands in the UK are Starmix, Tangfastics, Supermix, and Maoam, with Maoam being its own line of chewy sweets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maoam.com/lang/enGB/index.html|title=MAOAM|work=maoam.com|accessdate=27 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150719065925/http://www.maoam.com/lang/enGB/index.html|archivedate=19 July 2015}}</ref> They were once the distributor of [[Pez]] products in the United Kingdom, but this is no longer the case. Haribo makes [[Pontefract Cakes]] at their factory in [[Pontefract]], [[West Yorkshire]], and other locations.\n\n==US presence==\n\n{{Unreferenced section|date=December 2019}}\n\nHaribo had been imported into the [[United States]] for many years{{When|date=May 2017}} by German food importers and sold at German and other gourmet stores at \"gourmet prices\", mostly in bulk. In Germany, Haribo was not an exclusive gourmet product, but a mass market candy. When Haribo of America was incorporated in the 1980s in [[Baltimore, Maryland]], Haribo's gummi candies were introduced to the US mass market through areas such as drugstores, grocery stores, and discount stores. The packaging was translated into English, and package weights were adjusted to match U.S. candy price points and package sizes. A laydown bag was developed for the US supermarket trade, instead of the hanging bag commonly found in German supermarkets, and a boxed product was developed for theaters. \n\nOnce this was done and Haribo products in US-style packaging were introduced at confectionery and fancy food shows, Haribo became a popular item. Sales soared the first year, and gummy bears became so popular in the US, Haribo in Germany could not supply enough products, so the US market was soon flooded with competitors such as German [[Trolli]] and American [[Black Forest Gummy Bears|Black Forest]].\n\nOn 23 March 2017, Haribo announced they will be opening their first United States factory, a 500,000 sq ft (46,500 m\u00b2), 400 employee manufacturing plant in Kenosha County, Wisconsin, scheduled to open in 2020.\nHaribo products made in the US regularly have [[corn syrup]] and artificial flavors and colors. Production with artificial ingredients is cheaper, however, and the U.S. operation is poised to profit from this lower cost.\n\n==International distribution==\n[[File:Haribo Normanton Distribution.jpg|New Haribo factory and distribution centre located in Castleford, West Yorkshire, UK.|thumb]]\nHaribo plans to expand to China and Brazil. In China it has launched test stores in Shanghai and Guangdong. The US headquarters is located in [[Rosemont, IL]]. New production facilities opened in [[Castleford]], West Yorkshire,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-24471417|title=Castleford Haribo plant to create 286 jobs|date=10 October 2013|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref> (directly opposite the Normanton M62 Junction (J31)) in 2016 and plans to open in S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Best|first1=Dean|title=Haribo to expand in China, US, UK and Brazil|url=http://www.just-food.com/news/haribo-to-expand-in-china-us-uk-and-brazil_id130630.aspx|website=just-food.com|publisher=just-food.com|accessdate=28 July 2015}}</ref>[[File:Haribo factories in Europe.png|thumb|Countries with Haribo factories in Europe]]\n\n==Slogans==\nHaribo's [[German language|German]] catchphrase is ''\"Haribo macht Kinder froh \u2013 und Erwachsene ebenso\"'' (\"Haribo makes children happy \u2013 and adults as well\"). The German advertisements were voiced by [[Thomas Gottschalk]] from 1991 until 2015. In English-speaking countries, it uses the slogan \"Kids and grown-ups love it so \u2013 the happy world of Haribo\". In [[Hungary]], it uses the slogan \"''Gyermek, feln\u0151tt kedve j\u00f3 \u2013 \u00e9des \u00e9let, Haribo''\" (\"Child and adult is happy \u2013 sweet life, Haribo\"). \"''Haribo c'est beau la vie, pour les grands et les petits''\" (\"Haribo life is beautiful, for big ones and little ones\") is used in [[France]], while in [[Italy]] the song used during commercials is: \"''Haribo \u00e8 la bont\u00e0, che si gusta ad ogni et\u00e0''\" (\"Haribo is the delicacy that one can taste at any age\"). Similar slogans are used in other languages. The famed Haribo jingle music was created by UK composer Stephen Lee Vickers.\n\n==In popular culture==\n*Haribo is referred to by name in [[Watsky]]'s 2012 song \"Gummy Bear Hundrednaire\" off his [[mix-tape]] ''Nothing Like the First Time''.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bft9zX5VSWw</ref><ref>https://gwatsky.bandcamp.com/album/nothing-like-the-first-time</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Haribo}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.haribo.com}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Candy]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Germany]]\n[[Category:Brand name confectionery]]\n[[Category:German brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Bonn]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Rhineland-Palatinate]]\n[[Category:Ahrweiler (district)]]\n[[Category:German confectionery]]\n[[Category:Gummi candies]]\n[[Category:1920 establishments in Germany]]\n[[category:German snack foods]]\n", "name_user": "92.6.115.137", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haribo"}
{"title_page": "Nangal Sirohi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Nangal Sirohi\n| other_name              = \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = city\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Haryana#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Haryana, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|28.193161|N|76.132078|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Haryana]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Mahendragarh district|Mahendragarh]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| leader_title            = Sarpanch\n| leader_name             =\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = 10.4\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 10000\n| population_as_of        = 2001\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 123028\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = 01285\n| registration_plate      =[[List of RTO districts in India#HR.E2.80.94Haryana|HR]]-34\n| website                 = {{URL|haryana.gov.in}} \n| iso_code                = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-HR]]\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n[[File:Baba Kalia Toda.jpg|thumb|Temple of Village Deity Baba Kalia Toda]]\n'''Nangal Sirohi''', famous for the painted [[Architecture of Rajasthan|Shekhavati Rajput architecture]] [[Haveli]]s, is a [[town|Village]] in [[Mahendragarh district]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Haryana]].<ref name=\"tribh1\" /> It is 9.5 km from Mahendragarh towards Narnaul (15.5&nbsp;km from Narnaul) in [[South Haryana]].\n\n== History ==\nNangal-Sirohi was founded by ahirs of Khosya [[gotra]] whose ancestors came from the neighbouring Deroli Ahir village. 500 years ago, <ref name=tribh1/>The Nangal Sirohi village is situated between Mohinder Garh and Narnaul City on National Highway 148 B. The village was settled in 1526 AD by the two brothers who were come from nearby village Deroli Ahir. These two brothers are called two Thoak Bhagwana and Harbakash .The village is 9.5 KM away from Mohinder Garh and 15.5 KM away from Narnaul . Its length from North to South is 5 km and 2 KM from West to East. Its means It area is  10 sq. KM. approxomately.\n\n=== Havelis and architecture ===\nThis area which was earlier under the [[Jaipur state]], came under the  [[Sindhu]] [[Jat people|Jat]] ruler [[Maharaja of Patiala]].<ref name=tribh1/> Lala Tek Chand was first among them to build the [[Fortification|fortalice]] haveli.<ref name=tribh1/> Nangal Sirohi, 16 km from Narunail and 9 km from Mahindragarh, is famous for its historic [[haveli]]s built by [[baniya]]s who had migrated from [[Satnali]] 8 generations ago (c. 2002).<ref name=tribh1>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020622/windows/main2.htm Magnificent havelis of Nangal-Sirohi], [[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]], 22 June 2002.</ref> Later in [[Vikram Samvat]] 1959 (1902 CE), Lala Deen Dayal built an ornately decorated [[caravanserai]] in [[Architecture of Rajasthan|Shekhavati Rajput architecture]].<ref name=tribh1/>\n\nHavelis are located in the older Part of the village called ''Oopla Baas'' (upper residence), built by local trading communities in 18th and 19th century. These were built by Chejaraas (masons) and Chiteyraas (painters) summoned from [[Shekhawati]] region of the erstwhile [[Jaipur State]] of [[Rajpootana]], who painted the images of Shekhawati [[Sirdar]]s and events from the native feudal life. In one of the haveli there are paintings depicting Shekhawati Sirdaars, while in the vault of the other haveli there are scenes from the [[Ramayana]] and [[Hindu]] gods. The color pigments in the wall paintings of the later haveli vault have been remarkably preserved for more than 100 years now and look fresh.<ref name=tribh1/>\n\nSeveral of these havelis are facing neglect due to migration of their owners to other areas for the business. Havelis are of artistic excellence, academic and cultural significance, there is lack of awareness about their conservation or documentation by scholars.<ref name=tribh1/>\n\n== Social Structure ==\nThe population of the village id 8916 people and 4786 election voters. The village is dominated by the Ahir Cast with Khosya Gotra. There are 1400 household of the Ahir They are landlord and their main occupation is agriculture, They have 80% holding of the agricultural land. The second cast which is Brahmin with majority of Sanwalodia Bhardwaj Gotra who are approximately 120 families in numbers and have rest of the agricultural land. These two casts have ancestral agricultural land holding only , Other casts who reside in this village does not have any inherited land. They have only purchased land from others.. In other cast nearly 150 families are of SC(Chamar),90 families are of Khati (Carpenters) 40 families are of Dhanak ,50 families of Nai (Barbur), 50 families are of Kumhars (Pot Maker), 40 families are of Banias (Trader) 25 families are of Sunar (Goldsmith) 10 families are of Maniyar, 10 families are of Guwaria and 20 families are of Walmiki It is known from elder of the village that before partition of India there lived Mohmadan also, They were Mirasi, Teli , Nai and Chhippi by cast. They have left the village in 1947 during India's Partition \n\n==See also==\n* [[Madhogarh Fort, Haryana]]\n* [[Chunnamal Haveli]]\n* [[Dharampura Haveli]]\n* [[Ghalib ki Haveli]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n{{Haryana}}\n{{Mahendragarh district topics}}\n\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Mahendragarh district]]\n[[Category:Mahendragarh]]\n[[Category:Tourism in Haryana]]\n[[Category:Rajput architecture]]\n[[Category:Havelis]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Nangal Sirohi\n| other_name              = \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = city\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India Haryana#India\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Haryana, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|28.193161|N|76.132078|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Haryana]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Mahendragarh district|Mahendragarh]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| leader_title            = Sarpanch\n| leader_name             =\n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = 10.4\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 10000\n| population_as_of        = 2001\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code             = 123028\n| area_code_type          = Telephone code\n| area_code               = 01285\n| registration_plate      =[[List of RTO districts in India#HR.E2.80.94Haryana|HR]]-34\n| website                 = {{URL|haryana.gov.in}} \n| iso_code                = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-HR]]\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n[[File:Baba Kalia Toda.jpg|thumb|Temple of Village Deity Baba Kalia Toda]]\n'''Nangal Sirohi''', famous for the painted [[Architecture of Rajasthan|Shekhavati Rajput architecture]] [[Haveli]]s, is a [[town|Village]] in [[Mahendragarh district]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[Haryana]].<ref name=\"tribh1\" /> It is 9.5 km from Mahendragarh towards Narnaul (15.5&nbsp;km from Narnaul) in [[South Haryana]].\n\n== History ==\nNangal-Sirohi was founded by ahirs of Khosya [[gotra]] whose ancestors came from the neighbouring Deroli Ahir village. 500 years ago, <ref name=tribh1/>The Nangal Sirohi village is situated between Mohinder Garh and Narnaul City on National Highway 148 B. The village was settled in 1526 AD by the two brothers who were come from nearby village Deroli Ahir. These two brothers are called two Thoak Bhagwana and Harbakash .The village is 9.5 KM away from Mohinder Garh and 15.5 KM away from Narnaul . Its length from North to South is 5 km and 2 KM from West to East. Its means It area is  10 sq. KM. approxomately.\n\n=== Havelis and architecture ===\nThis area which was earlier under the [[Jaipur state]], came under the  [[Sindhu]] [[Jat people|Jat]] ruler [[Maharaja of Patiala]].<ref name=tribh1/> Lala Tek Chand was first among them to build the [[Fortification|fortalice]] haveli.<ref name=tribh1/> Nangal Sirohi, 16 km from Narunail and 9 km from Mahindragarh, is famous for its historic [[haveli]]s built by [[baniya]]s who had migrated from [[Satnali]] 8 generations ago (c. 2002).<ref name=tribh1>[http://www.tribuneindia.com/2002/20020622/windows/main2.htm Magnificent havelis of Nangal-Sirohi], [[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]], 22 June 2002.</ref> Later in [[Vikram Samvat]] 1959 (1902 CE), Lala Deen Dayal built an ornately decorated [[caravanserai]] in [[Architecture of Rajasthan|Shekhavati Rajput architecture]].<ref name=tribh1/>\n\nHavelis are located in the older Part of the village called ''Oopla Baas'' (upper residence), built by local trading communities in 18th and 19th century. These were built by Chejaraas (masons) and Chiteyraas (painters) summoned from [[Shekhawati]] region of the erstwhile [[Jaipur State]] of [[Rajpootana]], who painted the images of Shekhawati [[Sirdar]]s and events from the native feudal life. In one of the haveli there are paintings depicting Shekhawati Sirdaars, while in the vault of the other haveli there are scenes from the [[Ramayana]] and [[Hindu]] gods. The color pigments in the wall paintings of the later haveli vault have been remarkably preserved for more than 100 years now and look fresh.<ref name=tribh1/>\n\nSeveral of these havelis are facing neglect due to migration of their owners to other areas for the business. Havelis are of artistic excellence, academic and cultural significance, there is lack of awareness about their conservation or documentation by scholars.<ref name=tribh1/>\n\n== Social Structure ==\nThe village is dominated by the Ahir Cast with Khosya Gotra. There are 1400 household of the Ahir They are landlord and their main occupation is agriculture, They have 80% holding of the agricultural land. The second cast which is Brahmin with majority of Sanwalodia Bhardwaj Gotra who are approximately 120 household in numbers and have rest of the agricultural land. These two casts have ancestral agricultural land holding only , Other casts who reside in this village does not have any inherited land. They have only purchased land from others.. In other cast nearly 150 families are of SC(Chamar),90 families are of Khati (Carpenters) 40 families are of Dhanak ,50 families of Nai (Barbur) 50 families are of Kumhars 40 families are of Banias 25 families are of Sunar (Goldsmith) 10 families are of Maniyar, 10 families are of Guwaria and 20 families are of Walmiki It is known from elder of the village that before partition of India there lived Mohmadan also, They were Mirasi, Teli , Nai and Chhippi by cast. They have left the village in 1947 during India's Partition \n\n==See also==\n* [[Madhogarh Fort, Haryana]]\n* [[Chunnamal Haveli]]\n* [[Dharampura Haveli]]\n* [[Ghalib ki Haveli]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n{{Haryana}}\n{{Mahendragarh district topics}}\n\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Mahendragarh district]]\n[[Category:Mahendragarh]]\n[[Category:Tourism in Haryana]]\n[[Category:Rajput architecture]]\n[[Category:Havelis]]\n", "name_user": "Hukumbhardwaj", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSocial Structure", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nangal_Sirohi"}
